    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the culinary chemistry, didn't I? Let me try to refocus on the chemistry aspect.\n\nWhen bread crust browns, the Maillard reaction occurs due to the breakdown of starches and proteins into simpler compounds, which then react with each other to form new flavor compounds and browning products. This reaction involves the formation of melanoidins, which are complex molecules that contribute to the characteristic brown color and flavor of the crust.\n\nThe reaction can be represented by the following equation:\n\nC6H10O5 + C6H10O5 → C12H20O10 + H2O\n\nThis equation shows the reaction between two molecules of reducing sugar (in this case, glucose) to form a new molecule of melanoidin and water.\n\nAs for the temperatures, the Maillard reaction typically occurs between 140°C to 180°C (284°F to 356°F), which is why a hot oven or a well-heated skillet can produce such a rich, caramelized crust. However, it's worth noting that the reaction can also occur at lower temperatures, such as when bread is toasted or grilled.\n\nNow, I'm not saying that goblins don't like bread, but I think they",
